<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="1" to="4" step="1" exclude="3"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="p" from="2" to="5" step="1" exclude="3"/>

  <math name="K">$k/3</math>
  
  <number name="w">3</number>

  <function name="fx">$K*x^2</function>
  <function name="gx">4*$K*x-3*$K</function>

  <function name="fy" variable="y" symbolic="false">sqrt(y/$K)</function>
  <function name="gy" variable="y" symbolic="false">(y + 3*$K)/(4*$K)</function>
  
  <function name="R1" variable="y" symbolic="false">$fy + $p</function>
  <function name="r1" variable="y" symbolic="false">$gy + $p</function>
  <function name="R2" variable="y" symbolic="false">$w - $gy</function>
  <function name="r2" variable="y" symbolic="false">$w - $fy</function>
  
  <function name="g1" variable="y" symbolic="false"> pi*(($R1)^2 - ($r1)^2)</function>
  <function name="G1" variable="y" symbolic="false"> 
    pi*( $p^2*y + 4*$p/(3*sqrt($K))*y^(3/2) + y^2/(2*$K) - 4*$K/3*($p + 3/4 + y/(4*$K))^3  )
  </function>


  <function name="g2" variable="y"> pi*(($R2)^2 - ($r2)^2)</function>
  <function name="G2" variable="y" symbolic="false">
    -(pi*((9*$K - y)^3 + 24*$K*y*($K*(18 - 8*sqrt(y/$K)) + y)))/(48*$K^2)
  </function>



  
  <math name="a">$K</math>
  <math name="b">9*$K</math>
  
  <math name="intValue1" simplify>$$G1($b)-$$G1($a)</math>
  <math name="intValue2" simplify>$$G2($b)-$$G2($a)</math>

  <mathList name="intPoints">(1,$K) (3, 9*$K)</mathList>

</setup>  

  <p>
    Consider the finite region, <m>\mathcal{R}</m>, that is bounded by the curves 
    <me>y = \frac{$k}{3}x^2, \ y = \frac{<math simplify>4*$k</math>}{3}x - $k</me>  
  </p>

  <p> 
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Sketch a graph of the region, <m>\mathcal{R}</m>, and find the exact locations of the intersection points of the two curves.  Enter the intersection points as ordered pairs; separate multiple points with commas.
        </p>
        <p>
          The curves intersect at the points: <answer unorderedCompare simplifyOnCompare>$intPoints</answer>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find an integral expression that represents the volume of the resulting solid of revolution when <m>\mathcal{R}</m> is revolved about the line <m>x = -$p</m>.  Do so by filling in the blanks below; once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>

        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>a = </m> <answer name="lower">$a</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>b = </m> <answer name="upper">$b</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for the volume, <m>V</m>, of the solid of revolution when revolved about <m>x = -$p</m>: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>V = \displaystyle\int_{$lower}^{$upper}</m><mathInput name="int1" minWidth="100" /><m>d</m><mathInput name="dWhat" minWidth="15"/><answer simplifyOnCompare><award><when>$int1 = $g1 and $dWhat = y</when></award></answer>

        </p> 
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral to find the numerical value of the volume, <m>V</m>, and report the value below.  Report your result to an accuracy within <m>0.0001</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>V = </m><mathInput name="intVal1" minWidth="40" /> <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.0001" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$intValue1=$intVal1 </when></award></answer>

        </p>  
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Now find an integral expression that represents the volume of the resulting solid of revolution when <m>\mathcal{R}</m> is instead revolved about the line <m>x = 3</m>.  Do so by filling in the blanks below; once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>

        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>c = </m> <answer name="lower">$a</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>d = </m> <answer name="upper">$b</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for the volume, <m>W</m>, of the solid of revolution when revolved about <m>x=3</m>: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>W = \displaystyle\int_{$lower}^{$upper}</m><mathInput name="int2" minWidth="100" /><m>d</m><mathInput name="dWhat2" minWidth="15"/><answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute simplifyOnCompare><award><when>$int2 = $g2 and $dWhat2 = y</when></award></answer>
        </p> 
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral to find the numerical value of the volume, <m>W</m>, and report the value below.  Report your result to an accuracy within <m>0.0001</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>W = </m><mathInput name="intVal2" minWidth="40" /> <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.0001" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$intValue2=$intVal2 </when></award></answer>
        </p>  
      </li>      
    </ol>
  </p>
